I felt it.

136
00:11:25.945 --> 00:11:26.772
Look at this table.

137
00:11:28.208 --> 00:11:29.601
We certainly have
a lot to celebrate.


138
00:11:31.908 --> 00:11:33.126
It feels good to be back
home again, doesn't it?


139
00:11:37.261 --> 00:11:39.132
You have a beautiful home,
Mr. Beaty.


140
00:11:39.654 --> 00:11:40.786
Oh, well, you should
see it in the fall.


141
00:11:41.395 --> 00:11:42.396
Quail season.

142
00:11:43.920 --> 00:11:45.225
[woman] Has it been
in your family for a long time?


143
00:11:46.531 --> 00:11:49.534
No. I built this myself.
[scoffs]


144
00:11:49.926 --> 00:11:51.449
You know, when I was young,

145
00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:55.714
the word "inheritance" wasn't a
word that existed in my vocabulary.


146
00:11:57.455 --> 00:11:59.892
It's funny that now
it seems to become ubiquitous


147
00:11:59.936 --> 00:12:01.633
in the vocabulary
of modern youth.


148
00:12:04.375 --> 00:12:09.206
No, my father thought it was better
to rely on dumb luck or faith,


149
00:12:09.554 --> 00:12:10.685
whatever you want to call it.

150
00:12:11.338 --> 00:12:12.731
He gambled away
all the money he earned


151
00:12:13.253 --> 00:12:14.298
selling shoes

152
00:12:14.907 --> 00:12:15.952
to people who were
better than him.


153
00:12:17.431 --> 00:12:19.999
Shoes to people who would walk
more interesting paths


154
00:12:20.043 --> 00:12:21.522
than he ever dreamed of.

155
00:12:21.566 --> 00:12:22.872
Shoes people wore to work.

156
00:12:25.135 --> 00:12:26.179
[chuckles] Work.

157
00:12:27.398 --> 00:12:28.747
That's a word that seems
to have disappeared.


158
00:12:29.487 --> 00:12:30.836
None for me, thank you.

159
00:12:30.880 --> 00:12:32.229
Oh, come on, a little bit
won't hurt the baby.


160
00:12:32.272 --> 00:12:33.317
It's an '86.

161
00:12:34.318 --> 00:12:35.667
No one refuses an '86.

162
00:12:36.929 --> 00:12:37.756
Let's have a toast.

163
00:12:39.323 --> 00:12:41.847
To the Beatys, together again.

164
00:12:43.980 --> 00:12:44.719
And then some.

165
00:12:45.546 --> 00:12:47.244
[all] Cheers.

166
00:12:51.988 --> 00:12:54.294
[Ray] So, where did you
two lovebirds meet?


167
00:12:55.426 --> 00:12:57.384
Oh. [chuckles]

168
00:12:57.428 --> 00:13:00.474
Um, Margot led this psychology
lecture at the university


169
00:13:00.518 --> 00:13:01.736
that just blew everybody away.

170
00:13:02.781 --> 00:13:03.738
She blew me away.

171
00:13:05.871 --> 00:13:07.829
You should have seen it, there
were so many guys after her,


172
00:13:07.873 --> 00:13:09.527
I practically had
